         <h1>Albert Hague, 81, a Composer and Actor </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Albert Hague , a popular composer whose work included his Tony award-winning score for the 1959 musical '' Redhead , '' the much-recorded standard '' Young and Foolish '' and the soundtrack for last year 's film '' How the Grinch Stole Christmas , '' died on Monday at a hospital in Marina del Rey , Calif. , where he lived . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 81 . <br><blue>3</blue>Mr. Hague was perhaps best known for his role in the movie and television series '' Fame , '' in which he played the white-bearded , bespectacled , irascible music teacher . <br><blue>4</blue>The film 's director , Alan Parker , had wanted a real musician to play the part . <br><blue>5</blue>The film came out in 1980 , and the television show ran from 1982-1987 on NBC and in syndication . <br><blue>6</blue>Mr. Hague insisted he had always been an actor , however much he had seemed to be totally immersed in music . <br><blue>7</blue>With the humor he and his wife , Renee Orin , honed into a popular cabaret act in their later years , he explained , '' I was out of work for 59 years . '' <br><blue>8</blue>His song '' Young and Foolish '' for the 1955 musical '' Plain and Fancy , '' was another large claim to celebrity . <br><blue>9</blue>It was recorded by Tony Bennett , the McGuire Sisters and Nancy Wilson , among many others . <br><blue>10</blue>His Tony for the score of '' Redhead '' was one of six for the murder-mystery musical , which starred Gwen Verdon and was directed by Bob Fosse . <br><blue>11</blue>Mr. Hague also worked as a teacher and coach for hundreds of young actors , including Jane Fonda , Roy Scheider and Robert Redford . <br><blue>12</blue>His special expertise was preparing actors for the thorny process of auditioning . '' <br><blue>13</blue>My definition of an audition is a nervous artist who 's not quite sure whom he 's looking for who 's interviewing a nervous artist who 's not quite sure who he is , '' he once said . <br><blue>14</blue>He was born Albert Marcuse in Berlin on Oct. 13 , 1920 . <br><blue>15</blue>His father was a psychiatrist and a musical prodigy and his mother a chess champion . <br><blue>16</blue>His family considered their Jewish heritage a liability and raised him as a Lutheran . <br><blue>17</blue>He was 9 when his father died , and he and his mother moved from their luxurious apartment into much smaller quarters where she ran a cooking school for debutantes . <br><blue>18</blue>In 1937 , after completing high school , Albert was about to be inducted into the Hitler youth , but escaped with his mother by train to Rome , said Brian Raine , a writer who is preparing a biography on him . <br><blue>19</blue>The passport he carried identified him as a Lutheran . <br><blue>20</blue>In Rome he attended the Royal Conservatory of Santa Cecilia on a full scholarship . <br><hr><br><blue>1(4)</blue>: <m_str>last year 's film</m_str> (1_34) 	<m_str>The film 's</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>The film</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>It</m_str> (9_1) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>'' Redhead</m_str> (10_7) 	<m_str>the 1959 musical '' Redhead</m_str> (1_15) 	<br><blue>3(38)</blue>: <m_str>His</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (13_36) 	<m_str>His father</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (8_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (15_11) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_23) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (16_11) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_5) 	<m_str>his father</m_str> (17_5) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (17_10) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_12) 	<m_str>Mr. Hague</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (3_8) 	<m_str>Albert</m_str> (18_9) 	<m_str>Mr. Hague</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>the Hitler youth</m_str> (18_16) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_3) 	<m_str>The film 's director , Alan Parker</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (3_22) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (18_23) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (19_6) 	<m_str>Alan Parker</m_str> (4_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (1_60) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_3) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (